ay they choose - with the opportunity and support to live independently, to contribute economically, and to participate fully in society.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">We welcome this opportunity to respond to this </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">important investigat</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ion.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">We</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> will be focussing on the areas in which we can provide unique insight</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> as one of the largest voluntary sector providers of social care in the UK, and as an organisation delivering innovative integrated services across the country</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. Specifically, we </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">will look at</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">:</span></li><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The impact on the provision of adult social care of the 2010 spending review settlement and the ability of local authorities to make the necessary efficiency savings</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">; and</span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Progress on making efficiencies through the integration of health and s</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ocial care services.</span></li></ul></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">We </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">note that in </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Government response to the House of Commons Health Committee Report on Social Care</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">(Fourteenth Report of Session 2010-12)</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">there was a specific request that the committee consider</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> social care provision from the perspective of all those who </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">use it, not simply older people.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">W</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">e </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">would be </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">very happy to provide supplementary oral or written evidence to contribute to the committee’s understanding of the challenges facing working age dis</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">abled people in receipt of social care</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> in these difficult times</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Clare Pelham, Leonard Cheshire Disability’s Chief Executive, has</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> also recently been appointed the Chair of the Voluntary </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Organisations</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> Disabili</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ty Group (VODG) and so will</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> be well placed to ex</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">press the views and concerns of the disability sector to the committee.</span></li></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Executive Summary</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Below, we set out our concerns about the impact of the 2010 Spending Review Settlement on eligibility for social care, the provision of flying 15-minute care </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">visits, and the lack of focus on commissioning arrangements under the new regulatory framework.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Specifically, we are deeply concerned about</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">:</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span></li><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">he substantial reduction in funding for social care over the past five years</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> (ADASS estimate there has been a cu</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">t of £2.68bn since 2011)</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">;</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">he </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">decline in the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">number of people accessing social care </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">over the past five years </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">(25% fewer people are receiving social care support from their local authority today compared to five years ago according to the Health and Social</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> Care Information Centre)</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, at a time where the demand for social care is rising as the population ages, and disabled people’s life expectancy increases</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The increase in the proportion of 15-minute visits over the past five years (a 15% increase, based on F</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">reedom of Information responses from 63 local authorities); and</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The recent changes to the Care Bill, making it more difficult for the Care Quality Commission (CQC) to investigate local authority commissioning arrangements, as opposed to provider delivery o</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">f commissioning arrangements.</span></li></ul></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">We also detail our concern at the slow pace of integration between health and social care over recent years, and our fear that recent Department of Health programmes such as the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Health and Social Care Integration ‘Pioneers’</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> p</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">rogramme risk losing valuable insight by shutting providers out of the delivery of integration services. We also outline best practice examples of integrated delivery which we are delivering across the country.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The Impact of the 2010 Sp</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">ending Review Settlement on Social Care</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Eligibility</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#000000; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Since the 2008</span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> financial crash, and </span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">a</span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">s a result of the 2010 Spending Review Settlement, there has been a significant reduction in the funding for social care from </span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">central</span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> Government, and from local authorities. </span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">In a survey of the 152 top-tier local authorities in England, carried out by the Association of Directors of Adult Social Services (ADASS) in May 2013, it was found that </span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">£2.68bn will have been cut</span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> from adult social </span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">care budgets </span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">by 2014, and that further cuts of £795m are planned for 13/14</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt"><span style="color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">As a result of this cut in funding, alongside widespread changes to the level of need at which local authorities begin providing support, there has been a sustained fall in those</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> receiving social care over the same period. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">According to the Health and Social Care Information Centre (HSCIC) the total number of people receiving social care services across the country has fallen by 9% in the last year, and by 25% </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">over</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">p</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ast five</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Indeed, the Care and Support Alliance estimates that 120,000 fewer working age disabled people are now receiving care than did in 2005/06.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">This reduction in both spending, and the number of people receiving social care from their local authority, is deepl</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">y </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">concerning. Social care can be</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> transformative to the lives of disabled people – enabling them to work, to participate fully in their community, and to maintain the basic level of dignity and respect to which we are all entitled. As such, the rising numbe</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">rs of disa</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">bled people being denied </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">care likely indicates a rising number of people isolated from their communities, unable to work, and left to scrape by without the support they need to live the lives they deserve.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">We have been contacted by many disable</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">d people in exactly that position, who have told us about the devastating effect losing social care has had on their lives:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; margin-left:0pt; width:482.4pt"><tr><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:482.4pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Joshua, on the effects of losing care</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">“I was told that I no longer met the criteria… I can dress myself but I’ve had to give up w</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">earing socks. I struggle with shoes and frequently have to ask friends, colleagues, family and even people on the street to rescue my shoes and put them back on when they fall off.”</span></p></td></tr></table><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Conversely, we have heard from those who are at risk of losing their </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">social care, who have explained what they would be losing if their social care support was withdrawn:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; margin-left:0pt; width:482.4pt"><tr><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:482.4pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Amy, on what social care enables her to do</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">“It’s about being able to have the same aspirations as others. I hold down a job, live independently and I </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">am able to live life in the way I choose. I believe this is a fundamental right, but it has also given me an immense sense of freedom.”</span></p></td></tr></table><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">As well as being destructive and unfair, this reduction in support is also likely to be financially imprudent in the l</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ong run. Earlier this year we produced a report, along with four other disability charities (The Other Care Crisis) which found that </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">for every £1 invested in supporting those with ‘moderate’ needs (according to the FACS criteria) £1.30 would be recouped by</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> the taxpayer, and disabled people</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The report found that investing in social care resulted in reduced costs to local government, the NHS, central government and disabled people themselves to the extent that if Government made funds available to close th</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">e £1.2bn gap in social care spending for working age disabled people, it would actually lead to financial </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">returns of £355 million</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">There is strong evidence to suggest that both the human and the financial cost of reduced support for social care can be ca</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">tastrophic, and we urge the Health Select Committee to take a strong line in holding the Government and local authorities to account on their reduced expenditure on social care. While removing social care for disabled people may save some money in the shor</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">t-term, the evidence is clear that the long-term costs will be substantially higher.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">15-minute care visits</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">We recently published a report entitled  “Ending 15-minute care” which drew attention to the scandal of 15-minute flying visits, which often leave </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">elderly or disabled people having to choose between having a drink or going to the toilet, or between getting washed and having breakfast. The report gathered substantial national attention, including</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> an outpouring of support from across the country and po</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">litical spectrum, and a specific response to our proposals to bring an end to 15-minute visits from the Department of Health</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">We found that 60% of local authorities </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">are now</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> commissioning 15-minute visits, and that the proportion of 15-minute visits commis</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">sioned by local authorities had increased by 15% over five years</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> We also found that 15% of local authorities are delivering more than a quarter of all care visits in 15-minutes or less, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">leaving thousands of elderly and disabled people with inadequate sup</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">port, and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">with</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> their dignity</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> at risk</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Our research also found strong public opposition to 15-minute care visits, with </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">93% of people agree</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> that a 15-minute visit is not long enough to support a disabled or older person to do everyday things like wash, d</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ress an</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">d get out of bed in the morning and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">78% agree</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> that 15-minute care visits deprive disabled and older people of their dignity.</span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">In light of the contracting financial resources available for social care over the past five years, and the corresponding increase in 15-minute visits over the same period, it seems very likely that </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">the former has contributed substantially to the latter. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">But, as with reducing access to social care, it is not clear that the shift to more 15-minute visits will achieve anything more than a slight contraction in costs in the short run, and higher costs in the long run. We know that unit costs for 15-minute vi</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">sits are substantially higher </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">than those for 30-minute visits – largely due to administrative costs for providers, and travel costs for staff – and</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> that excessive use of 15-minute visits will lead to additional costs from an</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> increase in hospital admissions</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, a heavier burden on the NHS, and worsening health for disabled and older people in the long run.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> As such, any savings delivered as a result of these shorter visits will be negligible</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> over the long term</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Clearly, Leonard Cheshire Disability is ideally pl</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">aced to discuss the highly topical issue of 15-minute care with the committee, and</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">offer advic</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">e on a potential solution. Numerous commentators, from Government Ministers to local authority commissioners to the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">author’s of the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Cavendish Review have raised t</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">he problem of 15-minute visits, and we would be very pleased to </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">offer our unique insight </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">to</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> any solution the committee proposes.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Commissioning</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">There has been a</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> clear trend in recent years in local authorities to increase the proportion of care which is c</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ontracted out, and to reduce in-house provision. Indeed, anecdotal evidence suggests that there is now no in-house provision of social care to speak of in English local authorities, likely partly due to the tightening available budgets, and the higher cost</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">s of provision faced by </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">councils</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">As a result of this change in provision, the importance of commissioning has substantially increased, but while regulation of providers has been increasing over recent years – particularly in reference to the new approach</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> to inspections outlined by the CQC – relatively little has been done to ensure that commissioning practices secure good outcomes for disabled and elderly people. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Recent Government amendments to the Care Bill have brought this concern into sharp focus. I</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">nstead of increasing the regulation of the local authority commissioning process – for </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">it is</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> this process that usually defines the length of care visits provided, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">as well as the resources</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> available to providers </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">to deliver services –</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">the Government has inst</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ead removed the ability of the CQC to carry out regular inspections of local authority arrangements.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="26" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">While in practice, the CQC has not been carrying out inspections of local authorities since 2010, we are deeply concerned that instead of taking action to</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ensure</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> these important inspections </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">are taking</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> place, the Government has instead </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">recently passed amendments to the Care Bill</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> that</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> renders these inspections </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">outside the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">remit</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> of the CQC, without express permission from the Secretary of State</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">s in both the De</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">partment of Health and the Department of Communities and Local Government</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="27" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">At a recent meeting, a </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">senior Department of Health source said that the expectation was that the CQC would only carry out inspections of local authority commissioning in </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">“extreme </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">cases”</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> – a description which seems unlikely to refer to any commissioning arrangements currently in place, despite the widespread use of such bad practice as 15-minute visits, time and task, minute by minute budgeting, and a failure to pay care staff appro</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">priately or in line with National Minimum Wage legislation.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="28" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Only with a strongly regulated, and ethically constructed, commissioning model can we expect an </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">efficient and caring</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> model of provision to emerge. This model will need to take into account approp</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">riate market composition – ensuring there is a choice between private and voluntary sector providers, rather than merely between private sector options – as well as appropriate commissioning practices, and ideally it should specifically rule out the worst </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">excesses of the current system such as flying 1</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">5-minute visits.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="29" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">We worked closely with a number of Peers in the Committee Stage of the Care Bill to bring these concerns into focus, and the amendments submitted by Baroness </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Greengross</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> and supported by Lord </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Low were warmly greeted in the chamber – though no concession</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> w</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ere</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> secured from the Government benches.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Funding Social Care</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="30" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">We also have ongoing concerns regarding the ability of those with ‘moderate’ needs, according to FACs criteria, and those accessi</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ng higher cost social care services to continue contributing to their own support in light of the recent reforms to welfare support for disabled people.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="31" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">As Andrew </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Dilnot</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> noted in his review</span><a name="_ftnref7"></a><a href="#_ftn7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, where disabled people need social care support, but either do n</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ot qualify for full support from their local authority, or wish to spend more money accessing specialist care, they often use their Disability Living Allowance (DLA) to make up the difference.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="32" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">This is particularly concerning in light of the</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> ongoing migrat</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ion of disabled people from DLA to Personal Independence Payment (PIP), </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">which is expected to result in 428</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">,000 fewer </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">people receiving support, and many more receiving reduced support, according to the Government’s own figures. It is likely that these reduc</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">tions in support will have a knock-on effect on those who are currently paying for their own care – resulting in fewer people receiving the social care they need, and likely an increase in the number of disabled people unnecessarily hospitalised due to the</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ir inability to access the care they need.</span></li></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Progress on making efficiencies through the integration of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">health and social care services</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="33" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">As the committee has noted in previous reports, the pace of integration of health and social care has been slow, and in </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">some places </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">almost </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">non-existent. While we welcome the additional £3bn assigned to the integration of health and social care in the 2013 Spending Review, it is clear that this amount</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> is dwarfed by</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">individual </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">budget</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> of both</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> social care</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> provision</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">(around</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> £14</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.6</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">bn</span><a name="_ftnref8"></a><a href="#_ftn8">[8]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">) and</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> the NHS</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> (£109bn</span><a name="_ftnref9"></a><a href="#_ftn9">[9]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">).</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="34" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">While there are pockets of best practice, including </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">the ‘Help to Live at Home’ programme</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> which</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> Leonard Cheshire</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> Disability</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> is </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">undertaking in </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Wiltshire</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, in general the health and social care systems remain divided. This ha</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">s a number of consequences</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">for disabled and elderly people</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, some minor and some severe, which could be resolved, or reduced, following further commitment to, and funding for, integration.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="35" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">As an example of a relatively minor issue that a lack of integration causes people in receipt of social care, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">many of our service managers report that when disabled people in residential accommodation are required to go into hospital for an extended period</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> of time – whether in an emergency, or for a planned procedure – small, but important, details of the care </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">they require can</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> get lost. One of the most common causes of complaint is that the oral and dental hygiene of residents declines </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">substantially </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">while t</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">hey are receiving NHS care – because there is no comparable dental health provision available in hospital settings, or because staff are unfamiliar with residents’ approaches to keeping their teeth clean. This can undo months of good work at residential se</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">rvices, and leave disabled people more likely to need </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">costly </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">dental </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">interventions at a later date</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="36" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">It is our view that without a meaningful pooling of budgets between the NHS and the social care sector, that this continued failure to integrate will prevai</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">l. While the costs for the taxpayer will continue to stack up, these budgets will remain invisible to separate budget holders. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Where vulnerable people, particularly those with moderate needs, are often being denied access to social care in the name of effi</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ciency savings, there are clearly no efficiencies to be had when this results in an increased rate of admission to hospital, or the development of ‘substantial’ needs as a result of an absence of support. Urgent action must be taken to spur integration acr</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">oss both the NHS and the social care system.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Health and Social Care Integration ‘Pioneers’</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="37" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">While we </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">are very interested to see the progress</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> of the Department o</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">f Health’s ‘pioneers’ programme</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> and to hear more about the innovative pilot sites announced on</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> 1</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:super">st</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> November,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> we have some ongoing concerns about th</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">e scope of the programme. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="38" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Neither the programmes ‘national partners’, nor those eligible to bid for the project at a local level, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">are accessible to social care </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">providers – the organisations which are actually delivering care at the local level. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">While we understand that local authorities and other ‘pioneers’ will be expected to work closely with providers in their area, we feel that the programme has chosen not to</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> engage with those on the front line, who are currently working hard to improve integration between </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">health and social care </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">services</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, and that consequently a vital perspective, and source of good ideas, will be lost.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="39" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Providers are at the sharp end of socia</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">l care provision on a day to day basis, and it is</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> their </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">activities which will decide how, and whether, the outcomes for the ‘pioneers’ project will succeed. While we commend the Government’s efforts to improve integration, and service delivery quality, it </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">is clear from the expected project outcomes (at Annex A) that it will be the activities undertaken by social care providers, as much as those undertaken by local authorities and the NHS, that will decide whether the programme will succeed. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="40" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Shutting provi</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ders out of efforts to improve integration between health and social care services implies the imposition of integration on an unwilling profession, rather than an integrated and empowering model of co-production, which otherwise the Government is very kee</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">n to promote. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="41" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">In light of these concerns, we would be very interested to know how many of the bids the Department of Health received specifically mentioned collaboration with social care providers, particularly of residential care, and whether those that</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> did were more likely to be successful.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Best Practice</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="42" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Leonard Cheshire Disability is delivering </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">the ‘Help to Live at Home’ programme in Wiltshire which brings together health, social care and local authority services to deliver personalised, outcome-focu</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">sed support for service users whose needs have previously fallen ‘</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">between the</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> stalls’</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> of health, social care and housing</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="43" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The i</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">nnovati</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ve service supports </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">service users with a wide range of needs – from </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">reablement</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> to end of life care – </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">to achieve the outco</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">mes they are seeking, whether that is support t</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">o become independent</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> once more, or the option of dying at home, surrounded by their family</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="44" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The programme delivers efficiencies in a number of ways: </span></li><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">S</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">taff</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">are given additional training in both health and social care to ensure they can deliver </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">more of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">the support that service users need</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> in one visit</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, saving time and resources associated with </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">additional visits from </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">nurse</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> or healthcare assistant</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">s;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">A </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">‘fast trac</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">k’ support programme</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> is offered</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, which delivers social care within 4 hours</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> to those identified as in need</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. By ensuring that service users have the support they need, when they need it, this service delivers significant health benefits and cost savings</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">By </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">running</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> community based triage services, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">staffed by a district nurse, to</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">engage </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">service users in their community </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">and</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> deliver health support quickly, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">consequently reducing</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> visits to the GP</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">; and</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Working closely with supportive housing services, ensuring that</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> progress made in the fields of health and social care are not undermined by poor accommodation.</span></li></ul></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="45" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">By working collaboratively with health and housing services, and working from a combined budget, the integrated service in Wiltshire saves the community signi</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ficant sums of money, while also delivering higher quality care to service users – with clear outcomes in mind. We would be very happy to see the service, or variations thereof, rolled out to other areas of the country – to ensure the benefits are as widel</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">y felt as possible. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Conclusion</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="46" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">We are very grateful for the opportunity to contribute to this Health and Select Committee Inquiry into social care. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">November 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Annex A</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">P</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">ioneers in integrated care and support:</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Selection criteria, process and national support offer</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">2.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> Our expectations from pioneers</span><a name="_ftnref10"></a><a href="#_ftn10">[10]</a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Within five years, we expect pioneers to: </span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">be regarded as exemplars: </span></li><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 48.2pt; padding-left:5.8pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">deliver improved outcomes, including better experiences for patients and people who use services </span></li><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 48.2pt; padding-left:5.8pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">tackle local cultural and organisational barriers </span></li><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 48.2pt; padding-left:5.8pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">realise savings and efficiencies for re-investment </span></li></ul><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">have used the Narrative developed for us by National Vo</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ices, in association with Making it Real, to help shape good, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">person­centred</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> coordinated care and support for individuals in their area </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">have demonstrated a range of approaches and models involving whole system transformation across a range of settings</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">hav</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">e demonstrated the scope to make rapid progress </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">have tested radical options, including new reimbursement models and taking the risk of ‘failure to integrate’ in some cases </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">have overcome the barriers to delivering coordinated care and support</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">have acceler</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ated learning across the system to all localities </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">have improved the robustness of the evidence base to support and build the value case for integrated care and support</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> </span><a href="http://www.adass.org.uk/index.php?option=com_content&amp;view=article&amp;id=914&amp;Itemid=489"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.adass.org.uk/index.php?option=com_content&amp;view=article&amp;id=914&amp;Itemid=489</span></a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> accessed 31/10/13</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> Community Care Statistics, Social Services Activity: England 2012-1</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">3, Provisional Release, HSCIC, p5</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> The other care crisis: Making social care funding work for disabled adults in </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">England</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">, 2013, Scope, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10